40
00:02:21,897 --> 00:02:23,478
and that's something interesting

41
00:02:23,478 --> 00:02:24,759
and kind of unique about our industry,

42
00:02:24,759 --> 00:02:26,500
but I was a graphic designer,

43
00:02:26,500 --> 00:02:29,582
and I had just volunteered to test a local game.

44
00:02:29,582 --> 00:02:31,143
I was in Dallas at the time.

45
00:02:31,143 --> 00:02:32,804
I wrote a local developer and said,

46
00:02:32,804 --> 00:02:33,805
hey, do you need anybody to come in

47
00:02:33,805 --> 00:02:35,306
and play your game and test?

48
00:02:35,306 --> 00:02:36,086
They said,

49
00:02:36,307 --> 00:02:37,708
Sure, why not?

50
00:02:37,708 --> 00:02:40,811
Out of 300-some people who had emailed at that point, they picked me.

51
00:02:40,811 --> 00:02:43,473
I just got lucky or wrote a good email.

52
00:02:43,473 --> 00:02:46,555
And then once I was there, I just made an impression on the people at the company.

53
00:02:46,555 --> 00:02:50,119
And they were curious, what do you do?

54
00:02:50,119 --> 00:02:50,399
You know.

55
00:02:51,836 --> 00:02:56,303
outside of coming and giving your time for free to play this random game.

56
00:02:56,303 --> 00:02:59,508
And I showed him my portfolio and before too long I had a job.

57
00:02:59,508 --> 00:03:05,216
Totally circuitous and this was 16, 17 years ago so things have changed a lot but the core

58
00:03:05,216 --> 00:03:06,699
philosophy of

59
00:03:06,699 --> 00:03:06,759
it.

60
00:03:06,959 --> 00:03:09,160
You never know what's important, I think,

61
00:03:09,160 --> 00:03:10,461
is the reason I tell that story.

62
00:03:10,461 --> 00:03:13,702
Because you never know what effort and what strings

63
00:03:13,702 --> 00:03:14,823
you're putting out into the world that

64
00:03:14,823 --> 00:03:16,604
are going to be valuable, that are going to tie you back

65
00:03:16,604 --> 00:03:17,424
to the thing you want.

66
00:03:17,424 --> 00:03:20,106
So you're constantly being judged on your presentation

67
00:03:20,106 --> 00:03:20,566
out into the world.

68
00:03:20,566 --> 00:03:21,706
And you don't know which of those threads

69
00:03:21,706 --> 00:03:23,627
are going to come back to be valuable to you later.

70
00:03:23,627 --> 00:03:23,827
Great.

71
00:03:23,827 --> 00:03:25,428
I actually got into the industry somewhat by accident.

72
00:03:25,428 --> 00:03:26,489
I was actually inspired by Pixar.

73
00:03:36,237 --> 00:03:40,321
and then I was looking for an end to the film industry.

74
00:03:40,321 --> 00:03:42,502
So I graduated from school in Miami,

75
00:03:42,502 --> 00:03:44,664
and I quickly realized that there were no jobs

76
00:03:44,664 --> 00:03:46,706
in Florida for me at the time.

77
00:03:46,706 --> 00:03:48,688
So I moved to California with my suitcase

78
00:03:48,688 --> 00:03:50,649
and the workstation I built by myself,

79
00:03:50,649 --> 00:03:53,151
and I was lucky enough my portfolio got me a job

80
00:03:53,151 --> 00:03:54,412
within the first month.

81
00:03:54,412 --> 00:03:56,714
So I started with my first PS2 project

82
00:03:56,714 --> 00:03:58,576
as a character artist.

83
00:03:58,576 --> 00:04:01,758
So I was just mostly pursuing my passion

84
00:04:01,758 --> 00:04:03,300
for character art and character design.

85
00:04:03,696 --> 00:04:06,858
and I think that that translated over from film into games.

86
00:04:06,858 --> 00:04:10,861
I went to Ringling School of Art and Design

87
00:04:10,861 --> 00:04:14,043
and graduated with an illustration degree,

88
00:04:14,043 --> 00:04:15,364
thinking I was gonna change the world

89
00:04:15,364 --> 00:04:17,085
with my editorial illustrations.

90
00:04:17,085 --> 00:04:19,167
And when that didn't happen,

91
00:04:19,167 --> 00:04:21,629
I was lucky enough to get an internship

92
00:04:21,629 --> 00:04:24,991
at the old phone company 9X Science and Technology,

93
00:04:24,991 --> 00:04:27,533
where they helped me bridge the gap

94
00:04:27,533 --> 00:04:30,875
between all of the traditional art that I had learned

95
00:04:30,875 --> 00:04:33,017
and moving over into the digital side.

96
00:04:34,560 --> 00:04:37,081
Once I was comfortable with the digital platform,

97
00:04:37,081 --> 00:04:41,442
I moved over to a small children's edutainment company

98
00:04:41,442 --> 00:04:44,183
doing like 8-bit story,

99
00:04:44,183 --> 00:04:46,764
like click the page and turn the page stories.

100
00:04:46,764 --> 00:04:52,186
All the while really at home working on my real portfolio,

101
00:04:52,186 --> 00:04:54,847
going home every night and just grinding and grinding.

102
00:04:54,847 --> 00:04:58,428
And finally getting my big break at Looking Glass Studios

103
00:04:58,428 --> 00:04:59,889
working on one of their flight simulators.

104
00:05:01,527 --> 00:05:03,889
So way way back

105
00:05:03,889 --> 00:05:07,834
I thought the only way to get into the games industry was to be a fine artist

106
00:05:07,834 --> 00:05:11,318
And I was a terrible fine artist and I didn't get into fine art school

107
00:05:11,318 --> 00:05:13,260
so after

108
00:05:13,260 --> 00:05:20,428
Crushing rejection I ended up going to game art school. I dropped out which I might not recommend to the room but

109
00:05:20,913 --> 00:05:21,773
It kind of worked out.

110
00:05:21,773 --> 00:05:24,975
So, dropped out, moved across the country.

111
00:05:24,975 --> 00:05:26,976
Ended up doing contract UI work

112
00:05:26,976 --> 00:05:29,317
while doing some just day jobs.

113
00:05:29,317 --> 00:05:31,758
And sort of like Sean, I just ended up grinding away

114
00:05:31,758 --> 00:05:33,099
on my character art portfolio,

115
00:05:33,099 --> 00:05:34,699
got into some indie companies,

116
00:05:34,699 --> 00:05:36,860
and then moved on to the bigger ones.

117
00:05:36,860 --> 00:05:38,101
Seems like the story is moving.

118
00:05:38,101 --> 00:05:39,622
One thing I'd like to add to that

119
00:05:39,622 --> 00:05:42,303
is that I've worked with two other artists

120
00:05:42,303 --> 00:05:44,224
that I consider really high caliber.

121
00:05:44,224 --> 00:05:45,685
One was in pre-med.

122
00:05:45,992 --> 00:05:48,273
and dropped out of pre-med and again, self-taught

123
00:05:48,273 --> 00:05:50,433
and really just grinded away.

124
00:05:50,433 --> 00:05:53,293
And another guy came straight out of airline industry.

125
00:05:53,293 --> 00:05:55,094
Like, he was a legit airline pilot

126
00:05:55,094 --> 00:05:57,314
and he was just working on his portfolio

127
00:05:57,314 --> 00:05:59,655
and he just went straight from like airline pilot

128
00:05:59,655 --> 00:06:01,755
onto working as an artist on Bioshock.

129
00:06:01,755 --> 00:06:04,415
So, there are many different paths.

130
00:06:04,415 --> 00:06:07,596
I've worked with some great architects

131
00:06:07,596 --> 00:06:09,016
turned level designers.

132
00:06:09,016 --> 00:06:10,537
Yeah, that's a common thread.

133
00:06:10,537 --> 00:06:12,857
A lot of architects and people who learn CAD

134
00:06:12,857 --> 00:06:14,017
are sort of transferred in.

135
00:06:16,658 --> 00:06:20,480
All right, so this is the one that always comes up.

136
00:06:20,480 --> 00:06:21,841
You know, we always hear you've gotta have,

137
00:06:21,841 --> 00:06:24,082
you know, five pieces, 10 pieces, 30,

138
00:06:24,082 --> 00:06:25,383
whatever it is in your portfolio.

139
00:06:25,383 --> 00:06:29,205
There's always somebody putting a magic number

140
00:06:29,205 --> 00:06:31,206
on what people expect in a portfolio.

141
00:06:31,206 --> 00:06:32,667
What do you guys think about that?

142
00:06:34,006 --> 00:06:34,466
I'll start.

143
00:06:34,466 --> 00:06:37,967
I think the best number is take whatever you have,

144
00:06:37,967 --> 00:06:40,508
divide it in half, and subtract two.

145
00:06:40,508 --> 00:06:43,329
That's the correct number for a portfolio.

146
00:06:43,329 --> 00:06:45,190
It's just, people put too much stuff

147
00:06:45,190 --> 00:06:47,271
in their portfolio all the time.

148
00:06:49,881 --> 00:06:52,163
Seeing the variety of somebody's skills is awesome,

149
00:06:52,163 --> 00:06:55,487
but the thing is is that your portfolio is only as strong

150
00:06:55,487 --> 00:06:57,729
as the weakest piece in it.

151
00:06:57,729 --> 00:06:59,631
And so if we get, you know, there's some strong stuff

152
00:06:59,631 --> 00:07:01,553
and then we get to the end and there's something

153
00:07:01,553 --> 00:07:04,135
that's maybe, you know, not as fully well thought out

154
00:07:04,135 --> 00:07:07,318
or fleshed out or whatever it may be.

155
00:07:07,599 --> 00:07:10,162
we wonder if you have great taste, right?

156
00:07:10,162 --> 00:07:11,283
Because we're starting to kind of wonder,

157
00:07:11,283 --> 00:07:13,145
like, did you see those flaws?

158
00:07:13,145 --> 00:07:15,988
Were you able to understand why maybe this piece

159
00:07:15,988 --> 00:07:17,910
that you hid in the back just because you felt

160
00:07:17,910 --> 00:07:19,212
like you needed to have a gun in there

161
00:07:19,212 --> 00:07:21,474
or some other random kind of false belief

162
00:07:21,474 --> 00:07:22,716
about your portfolio?

163
00:07:24,197 --> 00:07:25,839
we start to question whether or not you're bringing

164
00:07:25,839 --> 00:07:27,720
that same quality bar to all your pieces.

165
00:07:27,720 --> 00:07:30,322
So if you could get somebody who's not you

166
00:07:30,322 --> 00:07:33,464
to look at them, give you some advice on the fidelity

167
00:07:33,464 --> 00:07:34,805
of the stuff that you're doing,

168
00:07:34,805 --> 00:07:35,926
be really, really critical,

169
00:07:35,926 --> 00:07:37,647
and then if you feel like something is weaker,

170
00:07:37,647 --> 00:07:40,049
cull it from the herd, get it out of there,

171
00:07:40,049 --> 00:07:42,151
your whole portfolio is gonna be better.

172
00:07:42,151 --> 00:07:43,292
We've hired people at Epic

173
00:07:43,292 --> 00:07:45,493
that had three pieces in their portfolio.

174
00:07:45,493 --> 00:07:48,135
A junior artist that made three amazing environments

175
00:07:48,135 --> 00:07:50,317
and took three screenshots each, and we hired him.

176
00:07:52,795 --> 00:07:55,296
Yeah, I would definitely stress quality over quantity.

177
00:07:55,296 --> 00:07:58,537
I think what you first have to ask yourself is what kind of games you want to make.

178
00:07:58,537 --> 00:08:02,958
Because I think one of the biggest traps is trying to do all the styles in your portfolio.

179
00:08:02,958 --> 00:08:06,240
I think that is sort of spreading yourself a little thin,

180
00:08:06,240 --> 00:08:08,420
and it's also muting your voice.

181
00:08:08,420 --> 00:08:11,842
So I would sort of approach it from, like, what kind of games do I want to make,

182
00:08:11,842 --> 00:08:15,063
what kind of art do I want to make, what kind of voice do I want to make,

183
00:08:15,063 --> 00:08:16,923
and what kind of position do I want to fill.

184
00:08:17,298 --> 00:08:20,459
because we're most likely looking for a very particular position

185
00:08:20,459 --> 00:08:22,759
and a very particular set of skills,

186
00:08:22,759 --> 00:08:25,820
and we're not looking for the jack-of-all-trades.

187
00:08:25,820 --> 00:08:29,821
Maybe small studios are looking for that,

188
00:08:29,821 --> 00:08:32,342
but mostly we're looking for someone who can come in

189
00:08:32,342 --> 00:08:33,642
and hit the ground running and do one thing very well.

190
00:08:33,642 --> 00:08:33,962
Awesome.

191
00:08:33,962 --> 00:08:40,684
Speaking of that, too, what about importance of a presentation?

192
00:08:40,684 --> 00:08:44,485
How does that impact your thoughts on a portfolio?

193
00:08:44,485 --> 00:08:46,345
So, I think this is ...

194
00:08:47,285 --> 00:08:49,946
you know, very much related to the previous question,

195
00:08:49,946 --> 00:08:53,367
like you're an artist and your entire job

196
00:08:53,367 --> 00:08:57,328
is to present things, whether it's in the video game,

197
00:08:57,328 --> 00:08:58,589
in the end product of the game,

198
00:08:58,589 --> 00:09:00,769
you're presenting things to the audience,

199
00:09:00,769 --> 00:09:02,290
whether it's in your portfolio,

200
00:09:02,290 --> 00:09:05,051
you're presenting your work to a potential employer,

201
00:09:05,051 --> 00:09:07,211
it's all about the presentation.

202
00:09:07,211 --> 00:09:10,733
Part of that presentation is the quality of the art

203
00:09:10,733 --> 00:09:13,714
that's in your portfolio, it's also how you present it.

204
00:09:13,714 --> 00:09:14,054
How many,

205
00:09:15,061 --> 00:09:17,223
Hoops, do I have to jump through to see your art?

206
00:09:17,223 --> 00:09:19,904
One of my favorite examples of the worst portfolio

207
00:09:19,904 --> 00:09:21,506
I've ever seen.

208
00:09:21,506 --> 00:09:26,109
Back when, you know, back in the mid-90s,

209
00:09:26,109 --> 00:09:27,430
I hate to say how old I am,

210
00:09:27,430 --> 00:09:30,092
Ed Looking Glass got a portfolio on a CD

211
00:09:30,092 --> 00:09:32,333
when they still came on CDs,

212
00:09:32,333 --> 00:09:35,416
and I was supposed to open a CD and put it in the computer,

213
00:09:35,416 --> 00:09:38,218
and it was all tied up,

214
00:09:38,218 --> 00:09:40,079
like it was supposed to be a presentation,

215
00:09:40,079 --> 00:09:41,740
like they tied it up with like...

216
00:09:42,655 --> 00:09:48,997
dental floss and it was like a bow and it was like opening one of those bubble packs

217
00:09:48,997 --> 00:09:54,438
with the, by the time I spent ten minutes trying to open this thing I threw it away.

218
00:09:54,438 --> 00:09:59,640
So that presentation completely worked against what you really want is get me to your images

219
00:09:59,640 --> 00:10:03,822
and show me what you have and present them in a clean and simple way.

220
00:10:04,032 --> 00:10:05,413
I think I just echo what Sean said.

221
00:10:05,413 --> 00:10:08,175
I mean, I think we're at a time where all you really need

222
00:10:08,175 --> 00:10:11,398
is ArtStation and then a handful of really good images.

223
00:10:11,398 --> 00:10:13,179
But in those really good images,

224
00:10:13,179 --> 00:10:15,661
if you're making a character, you've got to pose them,

225
00:10:15,661 --> 00:10:16,722
like drop them out of T-pose,

226
00:10:16,722 --> 00:10:18,043
get them in a good lighting situation.

227
00:10:18,043 --> 00:10:20,004
If you're making an environment,

228
00:10:20,004 --> 00:10:21,786
tell a story, light it well,

229
00:10:21,786 --> 00:10:24,628
set an atmosphere in that environment,

230
00:10:24,628 --> 00:10:26,389
and it makes it easier for us to hire you.

231
00:10:26,389 --> 00:10:30,152
If I could just piggyback on that comment about atmosphere.

232
00:10:31,042 --> 00:10:35,064
just for those of you who are aspiring environment people,

233
00:10:35,064 --> 00:10:37,866
that's the biggest single missing thing

234
00:10:37,866 --> 00:10:39,307
for me that I see all the time

235
00:10:39,307 --> 00:10:41,748
is people focus so much on the props

236
00:10:41,748 --> 00:10:44,290
and the creation of the assets

237
00:10:44,290 --> 00:10:46,971
that they forget that they're trying to message something

238
00:10:46,971 --> 00:10:48,552
and elicit a feeling from the person

239
00:10:48,552 --> 00:10:50,974
who's looking at the image.

240
00:10:51,534 --> 00:10:55,978
games are is just a series of images that we're composing and presenting and we're using those

241
00:10:55,978 --> 00:11:00,221
languages to guide the player and tell you where to look and where to go and what to see.

242
00:11:00,221 --> 00:11:07,327
And the soul of the environments get lost inside the pursuit of making a really awesome fire hydrant

243
00:11:07,327 --> 00:11:11,791
and we don't care about the fire hydrant. In fact, I would much rather have somebody who is a little

244
00:11:11,791 --> 00:11:16,395
bit weaker on the technical sides of the art because we'll teach you the tool, that's fine.

245
00:11:16,395 --> 00:11:18,857
If you tell an amazing story with an image then...

246
00:11:19,017 --> 00:11:19,818
You're great.

247
00:11:19,818 --> 00:11:20,838
That's the point, you know?

248
00:11:20,838 --> 00:11:22,980
So it was a great comment, I totally agree.

249
00:11:22,980 --> 00:11:25,041
Yeah, I agree, definitely telling a story,

250
00:11:25,041 --> 00:11:28,583
and I wanna get a sense of your aesthetic and personality.

251
00:11:28,583 --> 00:11:31,344
What are you gonna, what sort of story are you gonna tell,

252
00:11:31,344 --> 00:11:34,266
what sort of personality are you gonna bring to the product?

253
00:11:34,266 --> 00:11:37,388
And having a strong style and perspective

254
00:11:37,388 --> 00:11:39,429
