00:22:54,381 --> 00:22:56,442
So, less tools, more talent.

508
00:22:56,857 --> 00:23:00,140
That's a perfect segue to the next question.

509
00:23:00,140 --> 00:23:03,004
Do you guys expect to see content in Engine now?

510
00:23:03,004 --> 00:23:05,427
Like, you know, I know years ago it was like,

511
00:23:05,427 --> 00:23:07,589
hey, here's my awesome ZBrush sculpt with,

512
00:23:07,589 --> 00:23:13,396
you know, whatever, how many millions and billions of polygons.

513
00:23:13,396 --> 00:23:15,398
Now, is that really still applicable?

514
00:23:16,410 --> 00:23:19,653
You know, like what are your expectations when you see it?

515
00:23:19,653 --> 00:23:19,673
I...

516
00:23:19,673 --> 00:23:21,155
If I see like a...

517
00:23:21,155 --> 00:23:23,717
I'm just so over seeing really nice sculpts,

518
00:23:23,717 --> 00:23:24,558
to be honest with you.

519
00:23:24,558 --> 00:23:25,939
Like, and I'm a sculptor, like I...

520
00:23:25,939 --> 00:23:26,740
That's what I do.

521
00:23:26,740 --> 00:23:31,924
But seeing a portfolio of like just really high detailed sculpts

522
00:23:31,924 --> 00:23:36,208
and then it just stops there is the most useless thing for my team imaginable.

523
00:23:36,208 --> 00:23:37,990
I'm not trying to be mean about it, but like...

524
00:23:38,350 --> 00:23:42,172
There's so much more beyond that the sculpting is the easy fun part

525
00:23:42,172 --> 00:23:45,553
Then you have to make the low poly you have to bake it properly

526
00:23:45,553 --> 00:23:49,435
That's the light properly materials have to read well color theory all that stuff

527
00:23:49,435 --> 00:23:52,056
And you don't have to I mean as much as I love unreal

528
00:23:52,056 --> 00:23:57,018
You don't have to put it in unreal. You don't have to learn shader networks and stuff like that. You can use marmoset

529
00:23:57,018 --> 00:24:05,162
There's a plenty of of great tools that make it easy to show something in content. How dare you sir?

530
00:24:05,893 --> 00:24:09,455
I said I loved it though. I love you can use more besides fun, but

531
00:24:09,455 --> 00:24:13,617
But yeah, just the game development goes beyond sculpts, and I know that it's fun

532
00:24:13,617 --> 00:24:18,620
But yeah, you gotta you gotta go further sculpts still have a place obviously right like yeah

533
00:24:18,620 --> 00:24:24,824
Where they used to be like the pinnacle of your piece? Yeah, like it's the dressing now. Yeah, it's like the fun part

534
00:24:24,824 --> 00:24:27,246
It's kind of like concept art

535
00:24:27,246 --> 00:24:33,549
You know 90% of that is sketching and then you have the nice beautifully rendered thing right and it's like everybody wants to do the nice

536
00:24:33,549 --> 00:24:34,270
beautifully rendered

537
00:24:34,490 --> 00:24:41,916
Thing but the reality is your job is actually making like a game model. It's like making something that the team works with it's not

538
00:24:41,916 --> 00:24:48,702
You know getting front row on zebra central the the boring hard part is the job. Yeah. Yeah, it's the job

539
00:24:48,702 --> 00:24:52,525
It's 90% of your day is the boring hard stuff

540
00:24:52,525 --> 00:25:00,532
It's the UVs that you hate and it's the low poly and the optimization and making the LEDs and getting the materials right and all

541
00:25:00,532 --> 00:25:01,633
That other stuff that's the job

542
00:25:02,877 --> 00:25:05,157
It's nicer to see that stuff in Engine, yes.

543
00:25:05,157 --> 00:25:07,438
Whether it's Marmoset or whether it's Unreal,

544
00:25:07,438 --> 00:25:10,619
because that shows us that you've gone through the process,

545
00:25:10,619 --> 00:25:11,940
that you've gone through the workflow,

546
00:25:11,940 --> 00:25:14,741
and you understand how to translate the Materials

547
00:25:14,741 --> 00:25:17,081
that you're trying to create into what the Engine

548
00:25:17,081 --> 00:25:18,122
is actually going to show.

549
00:25:18,122 --> 00:25:19,042
Okay, so the next one, this is pretty easy.

550
00:25:19,042 --> 00:25:26,525
I think it's a constant question that we always face.

551
00:25:26,525 --> 00:25:29,906
Everybody wants to know, should I specialize?

552
00:25:29,906 --> 00:25:31,946
Should I be general? Should I try everything?

553
00:25:32,929 --> 00:25:35,850
What do you guys think?

554
00:25:35,850 --> 00:25:36,050
Yes.

555
00:25:36,050 --> 00:25:40,672
I think the answer to this one is know your audience.

556
00:25:40,672 --> 00:25:42,952
Who are you applying to?

557
00:25:42,952 --> 00:25:44,193
Is it a large company?

558
00:25:44,193 --> 00:25:47,294
You'll probably want to see specialization.

559
00:25:47,294 --> 00:25:48,774
Is it a small indie startup?

560
00:25:48,774 --> 00:25:54,256
They'll probably want to see a lot of jack of all trades.

561
00:25:54,256 --> 00:25:56,897
I think the answer to this is know

562
00:25:56,897 --> 00:25:59,418
who you are sending your stuff to and know

563
00:25:59,418 --> 00:26:01,338
who you want to be as an artist.

564
00:26:02,093 --> 00:26:05,376
Lisette made a perfect point talking about the animation stuff on South Park, because

565
00:26:05,376 --> 00:26:10,821
those people that were applying with mocap reels might have had a chance if they had

566
00:26:10,821 --> 00:26:15,104
customized their work for the job, but they didn't because they just kind of blindly sent

567
00:26:15,104 --> 00:26:16,745
out stuff out there.

568
00:26:16,745 --> 00:26:18,046
It's a perfect example.

569
00:26:18,046 --> 00:26:24,131
Yeah, we always are looking for someone to fill a particular role, so specialization

570
00:26:24,131 --> 00:26:25,192
is important in that way.

571
00:26:25,559 --> 00:26:28,841
I got into the industry because I specialized in characters.

572
00:26:28,841 --> 00:26:30,322
And then as I grew my career,

573
00:26:30,322 --> 00:26:32,224
I started to learn VFX and environment

574
00:26:32,224 --> 00:26:32,904
so I could be a lead.

575
00:26:32,904 --> 00:26:36,207
But it was through that channel

576
00:26:36,207 --> 00:26:37,928
that I was able to gain expertise

577
00:26:37,928 --> 00:26:39,949
in how to use a game engine, how to get my art to work,

578
00:26:39,949 --> 00:26:42,051
how to get, learn rigging.

579
00:26:42,051 --> 00:26:43,792
And it sort of branched from there.

580
00:26:43,792 --> 00:26:46,554
But so you're going to really most likely get in

581
00:26:46,554 --> 00:26:47,795
because you're very good at one thing.

582
00:26:47,795 --> 00:26:52,098
There are studios who look for generalists,

583
00:26:52,098 --> 00:26:53,379
but as at like a.

584
00:26:54,237 --> 00:26:56,399
I'm getting in the industry level,

585
00:26:56,399 --> 00:26:58,360
that's a lot harder for you to fill that role.

586
00:26:58,360 --> 00:27:01,442
I will also say we can all smell from a mile away

587
00:27:01,442 --> 00:27:04,724
the student portfolio that is just full

588
00:27:04,724 --> 00:27:07,106
of the various assignments to teach you

589
00:27:07,106 --> 00:27:08,747
the various aspects of making stuff.

590
00:27:08,747 --> 00:27:11,348
And it's so common, and please, please,

591
00:27:11,348 --> 00:27:12,629
please don't make that mistake,

592
00:27:12,629 --> 00:27:15,691
but it's like, here's the one gun we did in gun class.

593
00:27:15,691 --> 00:27:16,992
You know, it's like stuff like that.

594
00:27:16,992 --> 00:27:18,833
And you just smell it.

595
00:27:18,833 --> 00:27:19,754
You just open the portfolio,

596
00:27:19,754 --> 00:27:22,076
and you flip past the one mediocre character,

597
00:27:22,076 --> 00:27:23,096
the one average gun.

598
00:27:23,737 --> 00:27:26,638
you know, the poorly textured AK-47 from the thing,

599
00:27:26,638 --> 00:27:27,659
you know, it's like, it just shows,

600
00:27:27,659 --> 00:27:30,421
you're just going through the motions instead of-

601
00:27:30,421 --> 00:27:32,122
And unfortunately, they're all kind of going out

602
00:27:32,122 --> 00:27:32,742
at the same time.

603
00:27:32,742 --> 00:27:33,923
They totally- Graduation rolls around

604
00:27:33,923 --> 00:27:35,444
and you're seeing the same assignment

605
00:27:35,444 --> 00:27:36,404
like from the same schools.

606
00:27:36,404 --> 00:27:37,805
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

607
00:27:37,805 --> 00:27:41,487
So I would highly recommend to make your own vision

608
00:27:41,487 --> 00:27:43,789
of that stuff for yourself outside of the scope

609
00:27:43,789 --> 00:27:45,009
of the class assignments,

610
00:27:45,009 --> 00:27:47,591
because they never make for a good portfolio, ever.

611
00:27:49,810 --> 00:27:53,612
So this is another really common question.

612
00:27:53,612 --> 00:27:55,333
What format is appropriate?

613
00:27:55,333 --> 00:27:59,896
If I'm an environment modeler, do I have a demo reel?

614
00:27:59,896 --> 00:28:02,898
Is that the right way to?

615
00:28:02,898 --> 00:28:07,622
How do you decide how you present your portfolio, I guess?

616
00:28:07,622 --> 00:28:10,984
I'm staunchly against demo reels unless it's animation.

617
00:28:11,592 --> 00:28:20,376
But a lot of it is because if you're trying to show a character and you have a 360 degree turnaround,

618
00:28:20,376 --> 00:28:27,419
I have to wait for it to slowly pan around so I can see its back or something.

619
00:28:27,419 --> 00:28:29,880
All of that can be accomplished in just one shot.

620
00:28:29,880 --> 00:28:34,102
I can just look at one image and be like, okay, that's the full character. I don't need...

621
00:28:35,723 --> 00:28:37,425
four minutes to see a thing turn around,

622
00:28:37,425 --> 00:28:39,707
or I don't want to skip around and miss something

623
00:28:39,707 --> 00:28:42,189
that you wanted me to see, but I'm impatient

624
00:28:42,189 --> 00:28:44,390
because I am, I don't know.

625
00:28:44,390 --> 00:28:46,812
And I skip past something that's vital

626
00:28:46,812 --> 00:28:49,614
and could have been good, but you know.

627
00:28:49,614 --> 00:28:52,997
And again, it goes back to presentations.

628
00:28:52,997 --> 00:28:56,080
Show your best possible image, right?

629
00:28:56,080 --> 00:28:59,342
And if it's based on a demo reel, I could miss it.

630
00:29:00,880 --> 00:29:05,582
I think that surprises a lot of people because I hear a lot of professors and stuff in the

631
00:29:05,582 --> 00:29:10,684
game programs constantly pushing the video reels and we all hate them.

632
00:29:10,684 --> 00:29:15,366
But it's really common with people, they bring their characters with turnarounds and they

633
00:29:15,366 --> 00:29:21,970
have big crazy spine-blazed, I'm going to get sick watching your fly-through video thing.

634
00:29:21,970 --> 00:29:23,210
None of us want it.

635
00:29:23,210 --> 00:29:24,491
So I couldn't agree more.

636
00:29:24,491 --> 00:29:26,292
And they really enjoy your music choice too.

637
00:29:27,536 --> 00:29:31,099
Yeah, I have to say I turn off the music most of the time.

638
00:29:31,099 --> 00:29:33,861
Unless you're actually animating the dialogue

639
00:29:33,861 --> 00:29:36,823
and I need to understand that you're hitting the points

640
00:29:36,823 --> 00:29:38,544
and selling the personality.

641
00:29:38,544 --> 00:29:41,847
So yeah, don't spend an entire week composing a song

642
00:29:41,847 --> 00:29:44,229
because most likely I'm going to turn it off

643
00:29:44,229 --> 00:29:46,210
so I can actually just focus on the content

644
00:29:46,210 --> 00:29:47,031
that you're creating.

645
00:29:47,240 --> 00:29:50,942
You don't get extra points for choosing Tom Waits instead of a techno song.

646
00:29:50,942 --> 00:29:56,084
And I think for modelers,

647
00:29:56,084 --> 00:29:57,825
images and stills are fine.

648
00:29:57,825 --> 00:29:59,686
You don't have to do the 3D turnaround.

649
00:29:59,686 --> 00:30:03,928
I do enjoy new techniques that they're using, like Sketchfab,

650
00:30:03,928 --> 00:30:07,070
where you can upload a model and I can rotate it around and take a look at it.

651
00:30:07,070 --> 00:30:08,811
It's pretty cool.

652
00:30:08,811 --> 00:30:12,773
As long as it's not a billion polys and I have to wait ten minutes for it to load.

653
00:30:12,773 --> 00:30:14,253
So you have to think about...

654
00:30:14,607 --> 00:30:15,827
the art director on the other side.

655
00:30:15,827 --> 00:30:19,447
Like I've got 20 portfolio reviews to go through

656
00:30:19,447 --> 00:30:21,388
in an hour, maybe hour and a half

657
00:30:21,388 --> 00:30:22,968
between all the meetings and the scheduling

658
00:30:22,968 --> 00:30:24,728
and all the planning that I have to do.

659
00:30:24,728 --> 00:30:27,969
So I wanna get in, get out, understand what you're about.

660
00:30:27,969 --> 00:30:29,729
And then if I think you're talented,

661
00:30:29,729 --> 00:30:31,009
I wanna call you back immediately.

662
00:30:31,009 --> 00:30:34,130
I don't wanna have to wait five minutes for your model load.

663
00:30:34,130 --> 00:30:36,750
I don't wanna have to wait 10 minutes for your video

664
00:30:36,750 --> 00:30:38,211
because I just don't have that time.

665
00:30:38,211 --> 00:30:40,511
So I'd like to add to that,

666
00:30:40,511 --> 00:30:42,852
the being respectful of our time.

667
00:30:43,578 --> 00:30:45,779
I think also goes back to the presentation,

668
00:30:45,779 --> 00:30:47,859
a clean and quick presentation.

669
00:30:47,859 --> 00:30:51,441
It's, again, can't say how much we appreciate,

670
00:30:51,441 --> 00:30:52,381
like if we get a portfolio

671
00:30:52,381 --> 00:30:55,062
and we can immediately be into the art

672
00:30:55,062 --> 00:30:58,103
and see, like forget all the fluff, all the intro stuff,

673
00:30:58,103 --> 00:31:00,564
you know, the 20 second, like card

674
00:31:00,564 --> 00:31:01,784
at the beginning of the reel,

675
00:31:01,784 --> 00:31:03,645
like we just wanna see the art

676
00:31:03,645 --> 00:31:07,546
and you have more of a chance of us seeing your art

677
00:31:07,546 --> 00:31:08,487
if you just get right to it.

678
00:31:09,579 --> 00:31:12,720
So I guess the basic rule of thumb is if it moves,

679
00:31:12,720 --> 00:31:14,341
it probably dictates a demo reel.

680
00:31:14,341 --> 00:31:19,643
If it doesn't necessarily move, don't do it.

681
00:31:19,643 --> 00:31:22,064
All right, so let's talk about rejection.

682
00:31:22,064 --> 00:31:25,505
This is always the best part.

683
00:31:25,505 --> 00:31:25,885
Sean.

