00:31:25,885 --> 00:31:27,306
We all look at Sean.

685
00:31:28,321 --> 00:31:28,721
There we go, Sean.

686
00:31:28,721 --> 00:31:29,822
It's there, it's up on the screen.

687
00:31:29,822 --> 00:31:31,162
I got plenty of those.

688
00:31:31,162 --> 00:31:39,245
So back in the day when I was trying to apply to video game studios, I got a lot of these

689
00:31:39,245 --> 00:31:44,727
and I just kept updating my portfolio, sending it out, get rejection letters, repeat, repeat,

690
00:31:44,727 --> 00:31:45,728
repeat.

691
00:31:45,728 --> 00:31:53,371
And finally, it culminated with me getting two offer letters on the same day from Looking

692
00:31:53,371 --> 00:31:56,592
Glass and another company called Reality Bites.

693
00:31:57,802 --> 00:31:59,823
And at the time when I was doing this,

694
00:31:59,823 --> 00:32:01,644
I was kind of bopping around.

695
00:32:01,644 --> 00:32:02,325
I was freelance.

696
00:32:02,325 --> 00:32:04,547
I was not necessarily in the games industry.

697
00:32:04,547 --> 00:32:08,329
So I had a job, and then I was putting in the time at home

698
00:32:08,329 --> 00:32:10,931
because I knew that the portfolio I had from school,

699
00:32:10,931 --> 00:32:12,593
which was really illustration heavy,

700
00:32:12,593 --> 00:32:13,673
was not going to cut it.

701
00:32:13,673 --> 00:32:16,335
So I knew I had to put in extra work.

702
00:32:16,335 --> 00:32:18,677
But I originally told this story back when,

703
00:32:18,677 --> 00:32:19,818
the first year we did this panel,

704
00:32:19,818 --> 00:32:23,581
to show that just because you do get rejected,

705
00:32:23,581 --> 00:32:25,682
and even if you do get rejected multiple times,

706
00:32:25,682 --> 00:32:26,583
it's not the end of the world.

707
00:32:26,583 --> 00:32:27,283
It just means.

708
00:32:28,662 --> 00:32:29,882
maybe you aren't good enough,

709
00:32:29,882 --> 00:32:32,864
or maybe you're not the right candidate

710
00:32:32,864 --> 00:32:33,905
for the job at the time.

711
00:32:33,905 --> 00:32:37,307
Sometimes we look for very specific things

712
00:32:37,307 --> 00:32:39,949
from a candidate, and especially in the art world,

713
00:32:39,949 --> 00:32:41,550
very specific styles.

714
00:32:41,550 --> 00:32:44,432
So you may be a fantastic artist,

715
00:32:44,432 --> 00:32:48,935
but you may not be the style that we're looking for

716
00:32:48,935 --> 00:32:49,476
for the particular project.

717
00:32:49,476 --> 00:32:53,438
Yeah, I definitely think there's a great.

718
00:32:53,890 --> 00:32:58,352
mindset that a game developer has to have.

719
00:32:58,352 --> 00:33:00,893
I like to say 90% of the times we fail,

720
00:33:00,893 --> 00:33:02,094
and then maybe 1% we do well,

721
00:33:02,094 --> 00:33:05,115
and then 10% we're just kind of all right.

722
00:33:05,115 --> 00:33:07,796
So getting in the habit of just failure

723
00:33:07,796 --> 00:33:09,457
is kind of the default state.

724
00:33:09,457 --> 00:33:11,078
You're going to try to get things in engine

725
00:33:11,078 --> 00:33:13,199
and they're not going to work 90% of the time

726
00:33:13,199 --> 00:33:14,780
until you figure out your pipeline.

727
00:33:14,780 --> 00:33:16,541
And it's going to be the same thing

728
00:33:16,541 --> 00:33:18,301
when you're trying to get in the industry.

729
00:33:18,301 --> 00:33:20,082
You're going to just continue to get rejection

730
00:33:20,082 --> 00:33:22,423
until you get the yes, but it's the yes that matters.

731
00:33:22,899 --> 00:33:28,702
But if you let that first few no's discourage you, you're pretty much dead in the water.

732
00:33:28,702 --> 00:33:32,604
And it's sort of that grit and mentality of just kind of persisting and pursuing your

733
00:33:32,604 --> 00:33:38,248
interests and just keep pushing forward through those no's.

734
00:33:38,248 --> 00:33:42,430
I've been in the industry for 16 years and I have a very stylized portfolio and I get

735
00:33:42,430 --> 00:33:44,272
rejection letters to this day.

736
00:33:44,272 --> 00:33:48,374
And it's just sort of, I'm not the right fit for every position and that's okay.

737
00:33:49,648 --> 00:33:52,629
Sean loves that we show his rejection letter, by the way.

738
00:33:52,629 --> 00:33:57,051
I wish you'd show the one of the studios that are no longer around.

